The historic counties of England are included in the [Index of Place Names](/Index_of_Place_Names) (IPN) published by the [Office for National Statistics](/Office_for_National_Statistics). Each "place" included in the IPN is related to the historic county it lies within, as well as to a set of administrative areas.

## Administrative and ceremonial uses

At the time of the [2009 structural changes to local government in England](/2009_structural_changes_to_local_government_in_England), the ancient counties continue to form, with considerably altered boundaries, many of the [ceremonial](/Ceremonial_counties_of_England) and [non-metropolitan counties](/Non-metropolitan_county) in England. Some ancient counties have their names preserved in multiple contemporary units, such as Yorkshire in [North Yorkshire](/North_Yorkshire) and [West Yorkshire](/West_Yorkshire) or now correspond to another type of subdivision, such as the [Huntingdonshire](/Huntingdonshire) district. In some areas ancient counties have been abandoned for local government use and then later revived.

## Other uses

The [vice counties](/Watsonian_vice-counties), used for biological recording since 1852, are largely based on historic county boundaries. They ignore all exclaves and are modified by subdividing large counties and merging smaller areas into neighbouring counties; such as Rutland with Leicestershire and Furness with Westmorland. The static boundaries make [longitudinal study](/Longitudinal_study) of biodiversity easier. They also cover the rest of Great Britain and Ireland.

